# ZeroClaw Architecture Plan

## Target Stack
- Vite + TypeScript + pnpm for app/tooling bootstrap.
- Phaser 3 for runtime/game loop, Arcade Physics, scenes, animation, and tilemap integration.
- Vitest for unit tests and Playwright for end-to-end flows.

## Proposed Module Structure
```text
src/
  main.ts
  game/
    config/
      gameConfig.ts
      env.ts
      constants.ts
      physics.ts
    bootstrap/
      createGame.ts
      assetManifest.ts
      stageRegistry.ts
    scenes/
      BootScene.ts
      MenuScene.ts
      GameScene.ts
      GameOverScene.ts
    input/
      InputManager.ts
      commands.ts
    entities/
      player/
        Player.ts
        playerStates.ts
        playerAnimations.ts
      enemies/
        Enemy.ts
        Goomba.ts
        Koopa.ts
      items/
        Coin.ts
        Mushroom.ts
        FireFlower.ts
        Star.ts
        Fireball.ts
      blocks/
        BrickBlock.ts
        QuestionBlock.ts
    systems/
      CollisionSystem.ts
      ScoreManager.ts
      AudioManager.ts
      StorageService.ts
      TimerSystem.ts
    ui/
      HudScene.ts
      hudModel.ts
    types/
      assets.ts
      stages.ts
      save.ts
      events.ts
      entities.ts
  assets/
    atlases/
    audio/
    tilemaps/
    tilesets/
tests/
  unit/
  e2e/
```

## Shared Types and Contracts
- `AssetKey`, `AssetManifestEntry`, `AudioKey`, `AtlasKey`, `TilemapKey` to keep preload, scene use, and manifest tests aligned.
- `PlayerForm`, `PlayerState`, `DamageResult`, and `MovementSnapshot` for deterministic player logic and tests.
- `StageId`, `StageDefinition`, `StageProgress`, and `SaveData` for level progression and storage.
- `ScoreState`, `HudState`, and `TimerState` so gameplay systems expose data without tight scene coupling.
- Phaser event bus contracts in `events.ts` for score, coin, player death, power-up, stage complete, and reset events.

## Core Design Decisions
- Keep Phaser scenes thin. Put gameplay rules in plain TypeScript classes where possible so Vitest can cover logic without full Phaser boot.
- Treat `GameScene` as the orchestration layer only. Entity classes own local behavior; systems own cross-cutting logic.
- Centralize asset definitions in `assetManifest.ts`; all preload, integrity tests, and scene references consume that single source.
- Use a small event-driven architecture via Phaser events or a typed wrapper to decouple HUD, audio, score, and scene transitions.
- Build the player around a state machine early to prevent later power-up and damage issues from becoming scattered conditionals.
- Keep tile/block/enemy/item interactions behind `CollisionSystem` helpers instead of embedding collision logic directly in scene callbacks.
- Implement storage behind `StorageService` with a serializable schema version from the start to avoid migration pain in later issues.
- Add a separate HUD scene/overlay instead of mixing HUD text into the main world camera; this makes scaling and scene transitions cleaner.
- Design stage registry as data-first JSON/TS objects so adding `1-2` or more stages later is configuration, not scene duplication.
- Make responsive scaling integer-multiple from the beginning in `gameConfig.ts` to avoid UI/world alignment regressions late in the project.

